\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. P. alpina }(L.) Delarbre,{\i  Fl. Auvergne} ed. 2, 552 (1800) ({\i Anemone alpina} L.). Stem 20-45 cm. Basal leaves long-petiolate, distinctly pubescent, 2-pinnate; terminal segment not divided quite to the midrib, the lobes often recurved; cauline leaves similar, but with short, broad petioles. Flowers 4-6 cm in diameter, more or less erect; perianth-segments ovate, the outer purplish, the inner white, or all pale yellow, sericeous.{\i  Mountains of C. & S. Europe, from S. Germany to C. Spain.} Au Co Ga Ge He Hs It Ju.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp. {\b alpina} (incl. subsp. {\i cantabrica} Laínz, subsp. {\i font-queri} Laínz & P. Monts.): Outer perianth-segments white or purplish, the inner white. Achenes c. 5 mm. 2n = 16.{\i  Usually calcicole}.
\par 

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp. {\b apiifolia} (Scop.) Nyman, {\i Consp.} 2 (1878) (subsp. {\i sulphurea} (DC.) Ascherson & Graebner): Perianth-segments pale yellow. Achenes c. 4 mm. 2n = 16. {\i Usually calcifuge}.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28 The plants from Corse have been distinguished as subsp. {\b cyrnea} Gamisans,{\i  Candollea}{\b  32}: 58 (1977), but differ from subsp. ({\b a}) only in having broader, less hairy leaf-lobes and in being calcifuge.
\par 

